image.altText: Jonny Bairstow hooks

items.synopsis: England smashes 592 runs, with Jonny Bairstow stranded on 99 not out, on day three at Old Trafford in the fourth Ashes Test. Follow live.

title.children: Jonny Bairstow stranded on 99 not out as England leads by 275 on day three at Old Trafford

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Welp, it's been another pretty ordinary day for Australia, but Jonny Bairstow getting stranded on 99, when him getting to the ton was the whole point of the declaration, is objectively hilarious. Now Australia is pushing the proverbial uphill to keep this match alive. They need to keep a lot of wickets in hand through the second half of today's play and even then rely on the rain arriving in a big way on days four and five. England can go a long way towards levelling the series with a strong couple of sessions here. Can Australia's batters find their mettle?
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: England is all out for 592, leading by 275 runs

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Stuart Broad sliced that one and launched it straight up in the air. Josh Hazlewood settled under it and took the easy chance. That's 5-111 for Hazlewood, his first five-wicket haul since the opening innings against India at the Gabba in January, 2021. Jimmy Anderson strides out.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Five wickets for Josh Hazlewood as Broad holes out!

children.content: Stuart Broad sliced that one and launched it straight up in the air. Josh Hazlewood settled under it and took the easy chance.
That's 5-111 for Hazlewood, his first five-wicket haul since the opening innings against India at the Gabba in January, 2021.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Not quite the session we were expecting to be honest. England kept chipping away and scoring a quite an impressive rate but without really swinging for the fences at any point. Part of that was down to good bowling, primarily from Pat Cummins (1-105), who was so much better than he's been in the last two innings with the ball, and backed up by strike men Josh Hazlewood (4-105) and Mitch Starc (2-118). What score does England want? Will they bat on after lunch? It's hard to know what the plan is to be honest, England still scored 122 runs in that two hours at 5.08 runs per over.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Lunch: England 8-506 (Baristow 41), lead by 189
